Let R be a Ring. Let x\neq 0 be a nonzero element of R. We say x is:

a Left Zero Divisor if there exists a y\in  R such that y\neq  0 and xy=0;

a Right Zero Divisor if there exists a y\in  R such that y\neq  0 and yx=0;

a (Two Sided) Zero Divisor if there exists a y\in  R such that y\neq 0 and xy=0 and yx=0.
The way to remember left and right zero divisors is which side x appears.

Consider \varepsilon \in \mathop {\mathrm {Mat}}\nolimits _{2}(\mathbb {C}) defined as
\varepsilon =\begin {pmatrix}0 & 1\\ 0 & 0\end {pmatrix}
We see that \varepsilon ^{2}=0. Hence \varepsilon  is a zero divisor.

If x is a left zero divisor, then there is a y\in  R such that xy=0. But if x were also a unit, then
\begin {align*}0&=x^{-1}0\\ &=x^{-1}(xy)\\ &=(x^{-1}x)y\\ &=1y=y\end {align*}
which contradicts the condition that y\neq 0 in the definition of a zero divisor.

