p(x,y)=\sum ^{n}_{|\alpha |=0}a_{\alpha }x^{\alpha _{1}}y^{\alpha _{2}}
and so on.

Let R be a nonempty Commutative Ring. Let x_{1}, …, x_{m} be formal variables. Let
p(x) = \sum ^{n}_{|\alpha |=0}a_{\alpha }x^{\alpha }
be a formal polynomial, i.e., p\in  R[x_{1},…,x_{m}] with some \alpha  having |\alpha |=n being such that a_{\alpha }\neq 0. Then we define the Degree of p to be the non-negative integer \deg (p) equal to n.

Existence: Let z=x+\mathrm {i} y. We see x^{2}+y^{2}>0 is nonzero, so the complex number
w=\frac {x}{x^{2}+y^{2}}+\mathrm {i}\frac {-y}{x^{2}+y^{2}}
is well-defined. We just need to check zw=1, but the trick is (x+\mathrm {i} y)(x-\mathrm {i} y)=x^{2}+y^{2} and the result follows immediately.

Let z=x+\mathrm {i} y be a complex number with x,y\in \mathbb {R}. Then we define the Complex Sine function \sin \colon \mathbb {C}\to \mathbb {C} by
\sin (z) = \frac {\mathrm {e}^{\mathrm {i} z}-\mathrm {e}^{-\mathrm {i} z}}{2\mathrm {i}}
Similarly we define the Complex Cosine function \cos \colon \mathbb {C}\to \mathbb {C} by
\cos (z) = \frac {\mathrm {e}^{\mathrm {i} z}+\mathrm {e}^{-\mathrm {i} z}}{2\mathrm {i}}

Let n\in \mathbb {N}_{0} be a non-negative integer. Let a_{0},…,a_{n}\in \mathbb {C} be complex numbers. Then we call the expression
p(z)=a_{n}z^{n}+…+a_{1}z+a_{0}
a Polynomial in the variable z with Coefficients a_{0}, …, a_{n}. If n\neq 0, we call n the Degree of p usually writing \deg (p)=n. We call a_{n} the Leading Coefficient of p(z). When a_{n}=1 we call p(z) Monic.

Let n\in \mathbb {N} be a positive integer, let a_{0},…,a_{n}\in \mathbb {C} with a_{n}\neq 0. We define the function f\colon \mathbb {C}\to \mathbb {C} by
f(z)=a_{n}z^{n}+…+a_{1}z+a_{0}
Then the following all hold:

fr:ol.fr:li:
(Fundamental theorem of algebra, 2.0) There exists n+1 complex numbers w_{0},…,w_{n}\in \mathbb {C} (not necessarily distinct) such that
f(z)=w_{0}(z-w_{1})(z-w_{2})(…)(z-w_{n})
In other words, every polynomial function with coefficients over \mathbb {C} can be factored into linear factors over \mathbb {C}

