Let V be a Finite-Dimensional Vector Space over \mathbb {F}. Let B=(e_{1},…,e_{n}) be an ordered basis of V. Let L\colon  V\to  V be a linear operator of V. Suppose M(L)=(a_{ij}) is the matrix of L with respect to B. Then we define the Determinant of L to be
\det (L)=\sum _{\pi \in  S_{n}}\mathop {\textrm {sgn}}\nolimits (\pi )a_{1,\pi (1)}a_{2,\pi (2)}(…)a_{n,\pi (n)}
where the sum is taken over all n! permutations.

Let n\in \mathbb {N} be a positive integer. Then \mathbb {C}^{n} is a finite-dimensional inner product space, when we define the inner product as
\langle  u,v\rangle =\sum ^{n}_{i=1}u_{i}\overline {v}_{i}
This generalizes the usual dot product from \mathbb {R}^{n}.

The function f\colon \mathbb {R}^{n}\to \mathbb {R} defined by
f(x_{1},…,x_{n})=\left (\sum ^{n}_{i=1}x_{i}^{2}\right )^{1/2}
is a norm known as the "Euclidean norm". It is an example of the Norm induced by inner product.

Let p\geq 1 be a real number. Let \mathbb {F} be \mathbb {R} or \mathbb {C} (or a subfield of one of these). The p-Norm on \mathbb {F}^{n} is defined by
\left  \lVert  \vec {x} \right  \rVert _{p}=\left (\sum ^{n}_{i=1}|x_{i}|^{p}\right )^{1/p}
This generalizes the Euclidean norm in the sense that when p=2, this is precisely the Euclidean norm.

Let V be a finite-dimensional Inner product space over \mathbb {F}. Let U\subseteq  V be a subset (not necessarily a subspace). Then the Orthogonal Complement of U is the set
U^{\perp }=\{v\in  V\mid  \langle  u,v\rangle =0\hbox { for }u\in  U\}
Moreover, U^{\perp } is a subspace of V.

We see
\begin {align*} T\hbox { is normal}&\iff  T^{*}T-TT^{*}=0\\ &\iff  \langle (T^{*}T-TT^{*})v,v\rangle =0\hbox { for all }v\in  V\\ &\iff  \langle  T^{*}T,v\rangle =\langle  -TT^{*}v,v\rangle \hbox { for all }v\in  V\\ &\iff  \left  \lVert  Tv \right  \rVert ^{2}=\left  \lVert  T^{*}v \right  \rVert ^{2}\hbox { for all }v\in  V \end {align*}
Hence the result.

Let M(L)=(a_{i,j}) with a_{i,j}=0 for i>j (since it's upper triangular). We claim that a_{i,j}=0 for i<j. Observe, using Operator is normal iff norm of operator equals norm of its adjoint,
|a_{1,1}|^{2}=\left  \lVert  a_{1,1}e_{1} \right  \rVert ^{2}=\left  \lVert  Le_{1} \right  \rVert ^{2}=\left  \lVert  L^{*}e_{1} \right  \rVert ^{2}
but by expanding \left  \lVert  Le_{1} \right  \rVert ^{2}=\left  \lVert  L^{*}e_{1} \right  \rVert ^{2} this gives us
|a_{1,1}|^{2}=\left  \lVert  \sum ^{n}_{k=1}\overline {a}_{1,k}e_{k} \right  \rVert ^{2}=\sum ^{n}_{k=1}|a_{1,k}|^{2}
which implies |a_{1,2}|=…=|a_{1,k}|=0.

Let V be a finite-dimensional vector space over \mathbb {F}. Let L\colon  V\to  V be a linear operator. Let B be a basis of V. Then L is diagonalizable if and only if there exists an invertible matrix S\in \mathbb {F}^{n\times  n} such that
S[L]_{B}S^{-1}=\begin {pmatrix}\lambda _{1} & & & \\ & \lambda _{2} & &\\ & & \ddots  & \\ & & & \lambda _{n}\end {pmatrix}
where [L]_{B} is the matrix for L with respect to B.

Let V be a (real or complex) inner product space. Let L\colon  V\to  V be a linear operator. Then there exists a unitary U such that
L = U\sqrt {L^{*}L}
This is called the Polar Decomposition of L.

Let V, W be vector spaces over \mathbb {F}. Let L\colon  V\to  W be a linear operator. Suppose the positive singular values of L are s_{1},…,s_{m}. Then there exists orthonormal e_{1},…,e_{m}\in  V and f_{1},…,f_{m}\in  W such that
T(v)=s_{1}\langle  v,e_{1}\rangle  f_{1}+…+s_{m}\langle  v,e_{m}\rangle  f_{m}
for each v\in  V.

One class of systems of linear equations occurs naturally in Neo-Ricardian economics. Consider a hypothetical economy consisting of two industry sectors, wheat and iron, whose production processes are described by the system of equations (where the left of the arrow refers to the inputs at the start of the production period, and the quantities to the right of the arrows are produced at the end of the period, and then an annual market takes place where iron is traded for wheat):
\begin {array}{rcl} \hbox {inputs} & \to  & \hbox {outputs}\\ 280~\hbox {qr. wheat} + 12~\hbox {t. iron} & \to  & 400~\hbox {qr. wheat}\\ 120~\hbox {qr. wheat} + 8~\hbox {t. iron}  & \to  &  20~\hbox {t. iron}. \end {array}
The question we want to know: what is the exchange rate between quarters of wheat and tons of iron?

We can create a system of equations by introducing two unknowns p_{w} for the price of 1 quarter of wheat, and p_{i} for the price of 1 ton of iron. We assume society is in a "self reproducing state", in the sense that the wheat sector exchanges enough wheat-for-iron to continue producing wheat (and the iron sector exchanges enough iron-for-wheat to continue producing iron):
\begin {array}{rcl}     280p_{w} + 12p_{i} &=& 400p_{w}\\     120p_{w} + 8p_{i} &=& 20p_{i}. \end {array}
We can rewrite the first equation (by subtracting both sides by 280p_{w}):
\begin {array}{rcl}     12p_{i} &=& 120p_{w}\\     120p_{w} + 8p_{i} &=& 20p_{i}. \end {array}
Then we rewrite the second equation (by subtracting both sides by 8p_{i}):
\begin {array}{rcl}     12p_{i} &=& 120p_{w}\\     120p_{w} &=& 12p_{i}. \end {array}
These are redundant equations! We end up with a class of solutions, described by
\boxed {10p_{w} = p_{i},}
that is to say, the price of 1 ton iron is equal to the price of 10 quarters of wheat.

More generally, a System of m Linear Equations in n Unknowns  x_{1}, …, x_{n} (where the subscripts are Indices to append to one symbol x a number or "dummy variable" [a variable ranging over the index values], giving us any number of variables for the price of one symbol) looks like:
\begin {array}{rcl} a_{1,1}x_{1} + a_{1,2}x_{2} + … + a_{1,n}x_{n} &=& b_{1}\\ a_{2,1}x_{1} + a_{2,2}x_{2} + … + a_{2,n}x_{n} &=& b_{2}\\ \vdots \quad  \qquad \vdots \quad \qquad \ddots \quad \qquad \vdots \quad  & \vdots  & \vdots \\ a_{m,1}x_{1} + a_{m,2}x_{2} + … + a_{m,n}x_{n} &=& b_{m} \end {array}
where b_{1}, …, b_{m} are m real constants, and we have a_{1,1}, a_{1,2}, …, a_{m,n} be mn real constants called the Coefficients.

One method to find a solution, which has been taught to high school students for decades, is to take the first equation and use it to rewrite one variable in terms of the remaining. For example, in:
\begin {array}{rcrcrcl}     0      & + & 2x_{2} & + & 3x_{3} & = & 5\\     2x_{1} & + & 0      & + & 3x_{3} &=& -1\\     x_{1}  & + & x_{2}  & + & x_{3} &=& 1.   \end {array}
We would use the first equation to substitute x_{2}=(5 - 3x_{3})/2 in the remaining equations, and discard the first equation, giving us:
\begin {array}{rcrcrcl}     2x_{1} & + & 0      & + & 3x_{3} &=& -1\\     x_{1}  & + & \displaystyle \left (\frac {5 - 3x_{3}}{2}\right )  & + & x_{3} &=& 1.   \end {array}
We do this again, to use the first equation to write x_{1} = (-1-3x_{3})/2, and plug this into the last equation, which gives us a value for x_{3}.

Let m, n be positive integers. We define an m-by-n Matrix \mathbf {A} to be a rectangular array of mn real [or complex] numbers arranged in m horizontal Rows and n vertical Columns, written:
\mathbf {A} = \left (\begin {array}{cccccc}   a_{11} & a_{12} & … & a_{1j} & … & a_{1n} \\ a_{21} & a_{22} & … & a_{2j} & … & a_{2n}  \\ \vdots  & \vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots  \\ a_{i1} & a_{i2} & … & a_{ij} & … & a_{in} \\ \vdots  & \vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots  \\ a_{m1} & a_{m2} & …   & a_{mj} & …  & a_{mn}  \end {array}\right ) \begin {array}{c}   \\   \gets  i^{\text {th}}\hbox {\ row} \end {array}
We have highlighted the i^{\text {th}} row, and the j^{\text {th}} column.

For any positive integer n, we have the n\times  n Identity Matrix to be
\mathbf {I}_{n} = (\delta _{i,j}) = \begin {cases}1 &\hbox {if }i=j,\\     0 &\hbox {if }i\neq  j   \end {cases}
where the components \delta _{i,j} are referred to as the Kronecker Delta.

Let r, s be numbers and \mathbf {A}, \mathbf {B} be appropriately sized matrices. Then the following hold:

r(s\mathbf {A})=(rs)\mathbf {A}

(r+s)\mathbf {A}=r\mathbf {A}+s\mathbf {A} (distributivity)

r(\mathbf {A}+\mathbf {B})=r\mathbf {A}+r\mathbf {B}

Let \mathbf {A} be an n\times  n square matrix. We can introduce two matrices
\mathbf {A}_{\text {ant}}=\frac {\mathbf {A}-\mathbf {A}^{\mathsf {T}}}{2}
which is the "antisymmetric part" of \mathbf {A}, and
\mathbf {A}_{\text {sym}}=\frac {\mathbf {A}+\mathbf {A}^{\mathsf {T}}}{2}
which is the "symmetric part" of \mathbf {A}. Prove or find a counter-example:
\mathbf {A} = \mathbf {A}_{\text {ant}}+\mathbf {A}_{\text {sym}}.

If we look at a parallelogram in the real plane, then we can describe two edges using vectors \vec {v}=(x_{1},y_{1}) and \vec {w}=(x_{2},y_{2}). Its area is precisely:
A = \det \begin {pmatrix}x_{1} & x_{2}\\y_{1} & y_{2}\end {pmatrix}
This is taught to students in calculus. Similarly, if we extend our discussion to a parallelipid in three dimensions, we would have three vectors and the volume would be the determinant of the matrix whose columns are these column vectors.

